WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:23.040
I'm Nick Pylypiw, Director of Data Science at Cape Fear Collective, and today I'd like

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:30.760
to talk to you about our Racial Equity Dashboard.

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.720
Cape Fear Collective is a non-profit based in Wilmington, North Carolina.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:39.400
We're committed to using our expertise in data science to support frontline organizations

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:45.799
in southeastern North Carolina in their fight against poverty, racism, poor health and education

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:51.160
outcomes, and socioeconomic disparities.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:57.240
Although we are primarily an R shop, we also use Tableau, ArcGIS, Python, and SQL in our

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:04.279
analytics ecosystem as we ingest, store, analyze, and socialize data from a variety of public

00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:09.919
and partner sources.

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:14.040
Our Racial Equity Dashboard is built in Shiny and ggplot.

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:20.199
The framework houses tabs as separate modules for each category of data stories.

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:26.040
The landing page contains a brief introduction to the dashboard itself, our email address,

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:35.339
and a tab navigation bar for the data story categories across the top.

00:01:35.339 --> 00:01:41.839
Each of these tabs follows the same format, a brief introduction to the category, followed

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:51.720
by two to five visualizations and stories.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:54.959
Let's walk through one of those stories now.

00:01:54.959 --> 00:02:00.040
The definition box tells us that pregnancy-related mortality ratio, which is pregnancy-related

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:06.959
deaths per 100,000 live births, is often used as an indicator of a nation's health.

00:02:06.959 --> 00:02:12.639
The expandable explanation box gives the viewer additional context about how to interpret

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:15.759
the visualization.

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:21.039
This plot shows the 30-year trend of the pregnancy-related mortality ratio of the U.S. compared to select

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:23.119
economic peers.

00:02:23.119 --> 00:02:28.960
Though these five nations began the 90s at the same level, the U.S. has since deviated

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:33.559
from the pack, nearly tripling its maternal mortality.

00:02:33.559 --> 00:02:43.720
The country is currently 56th in the world.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:47.839
We often hear of pregnancy-related complications due to age.

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:53.240
For white mothers, this risk becomes apparent around 35 years old.

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:57.279
In black mothers, the increase starts much earlier.

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:03.199
The resulting gap means black women aged 40 or older have a pregnancy-related mortality

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:09.119
ratio almost four times that of their white peers.

00:03:09.119 --> 00:03:12.279
Educational attainment is another indicator of disparity.

00:03:12.279 --> 00:03:16.520
A college education appears to correlate with a lower pregnancy-related mortality ratio

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:29.320
for a white woman, but has little to no impact for a black woman.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:34.279
Looking specifically at North Carolina, we were able to identify a roadmap of interventions

00:03:34.279 --> 00:03:39.440
based on high-risk pregnancy factors and have shared these with our community partners.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:44.160
For example, increased access to prenatal care and pregnancy testing would have a significant

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:50.000
impact on pregnancy-related mortality ratio.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.679
Over the next several months, we'll be aligning our community data platform, including insights

00:03:54.679 --> 00:04:02.039
from this racial equity dashboard, with the statewide Healthy North Carolina 2030 initiative.

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:08.839
This will allow us to set attainable, data-driven local goals with a focus on equity and accountability

00:04:08.839 --> 00:04:15.360
through shared measurement.

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:20.200
I invite you to explore the rest of the dashboard and to visit our website to learn more about

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:23.079
the work we are doing in the Cape Fear region.

00:04:23.079 --> 00:04:27.640
Please also contact me if you're interested in volunteer opportunities, contributing to

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:32.799
our social impact investment fund, or if you just want to chat about the data.

00:04:32.799 --> 00:04:33.160
Thank you.

